Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Slice @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a
drizzle of @oil{drizzle}, @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{pinch}. Roast on top rack until
lightly browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Cut broccoli florets into bite-size pieces if necessary. Swap in @broccoli florets{8%ounce} for potatoes; roast ~{12-15%minutes}. Save potatoes for another use.

== Ancho BBQ Sauce ==

Meanwhile, peel and slice @red onion{1} into 1⁄4-inch-thick rounds, keeping layers intact. Halve @potato buns{2}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @red pepper jam{1%unit}, @ancho chili powder{1%teaspoon}, @BBQ sauce{4%tablespoon}, and @water{2%tsp}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

== Griddled Onion ==

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion rounds and cook until tender and browned at the edges, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Season with salt and pepper. Transfer to a #plate{}.

== Patties ==

Meanwhile, in a #large bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, @salt{pinch}, and
@pepper{pinch}. Form into two patties (four patties for 4 servings), each slightly
wider than a burger bun.

> For 4 servings, double the beef to 20 ounces.

== Cooking ==

Once onion rounds are done, heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

While patties cook, toast buns until golden brown. Evenly spread cut sides with half the ancho BBQ sauce (you'll use the rest in the next step).

Add @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} to bowl with remaining ancho BBQ sauce; stir to combine.

Fill buns with patties and griddled onion. Divide burgers and potato wedges between plates. Serve BBQ mayo on the side for dipping.